{"/service/ndnp/mthi/batch_mthi_hobson_ver01/data/sn86075250/00517178974/1930111401/0368.xml":{"full_text":"Page Four\nThe Harlem News\nEstablished October 8, 1866\nGBO. H. TOUT, Editor\nMEMBER MONTANA PRESS ASSOCIATION\nRraMKER. NATIONAL EDITORIAL ASSOCIATION\nPublished every Friday at Harlem, Montana, where\nit is entered in the postoffice as second class mail\nmatter.\nSUBSCRIPTION RATES\nPer copy\nShx months 1.25\nOne year 2.00\nEXPLANATORY\nAll subscriptions expire on the first day of the\nmonth. If the date on the margin of the wrapper oppo\nsite your name is 12-1-30, you are paid to December 1,\n1930, and your paper will be stopped on that date\nunless renewed.\nCHANGE OF ADDRESS\nLn requesting change of address, always give the\nold as well as the new address and write plainly. If\n\u2022hange in date opposite your name is not made cor\nrectly. notify us at once. Advice concerning errors in\nAddress or date given prompt attention.\nFRIDAY, NOVEMBER 14, 1930\nBUSINESS CONFIDENCE WEEK\nHARLEM BUSINESSMEN, in an effort to keep\nthe wheels of trade rotating, and to encourage\nwise expenditure, have set next week aside as a\nbusiness revival period. This is in line with what\ncities all over the nation arc doing. People arc being\nurged to buy now' the things which they need and can\nafford and the merchants are meeting them halfway\nby offering at this time special values in staple lines\nof goods.\nUnwise spending is not encouraged, but those who\nhave money are asked to step forward now and pur\nchase the things thoy need rather thun delay their\npurchases to some distant date. The local business\nhouses will be directly benefited, as will the\npurchaser who gets the tilings he needs at saving\nprices. Lowering the moiuhant's stock will lead to\nhis placing orders for replenishment which will in turn\nassist in keeping the wheels of industry going in those\ncenters where the depression is felt more keenly than\nwe of a rural community can realize. We may not be\nfinancially situated to contribute money to the allevia\ntion of the unemployment situation, but indirectly we\ncun. through carrying on our ordinary expenditures,\ndo our bit toward maintaining employment at a normal\nlevel.\nHelp yourselves by buying now ami saving. Throw\naway your smoked glasses and look for the bettor\ntimes ahead. We may not be able to give employ\nment to some one in need, but wo can spend wisely\nnow for things wo need, thus contributing to the\nwelfare of our community.\nTIIE BILLBOARD NUISANCE\nWESTCHESTER COUNTY, Now York, has set\nan example which every county in the United\nStates might well follow.\nPoster and billboard advertising is absolutely\ncontrolled by the county authorities and is prohibited\nexcept under certain specified conditions where out\ndoor advertising is not an offense to the eye and a\nblot upon the landscape.\nDuring the recent election campaign, some of thi*\npoliticians in Westchester County decided that the\nlaw was meant for ordinary folks and not for them.\nThey had the shock of their lives when their cam\npaign posters, tacked up in the customary manner on\nfences, trees and telegraph poles along the roadside\nwere torn down by county officials of their own\nparty. They blustered and protested, but to no avail.\nBorne of them were wise enough to avoid antagonizing\npublic sentiment and made no fuss about their inabil\nity to dsiplay their electioneering handbills.\nTimes have changed, indeed, when politicians\ncannot violate even a simple law like that with\nimpunity. The history of politics in America is that\nthe man in political office immediately regards himself\nnot as the servant of the people, but as their master.\nThe worst of it is, he frequently gets away with it.\nBut there are somo things on which public sentiment\nis crystallizing so strongly that even the politicians\ndo not dare to run counter to it. One of these things\nis offensive billboard advertising. Some day adver\ntisers will also wake up to the fact that most people\nare offended rather than impressed by advertising\nmatter forced upon their eyes when they are trying\nto enjoy the beauties of the out-of-doors.\nUNFAIR COMPETITION\nIN ADDRESSING the American Bankers' Associa\ntion in Cleveland recently, President Hoover said:\n\"I have never believed that our form of gov\nernment could satisfactorily solve economic prob\nlems by direct action\u2014could successfully conduct\nbusiness institutions. The Government can and\nmust cure abuses.\"\nWhat a howl would go up from the business\nworld if the Government of the United States, merely\nbecause it happens to have the necessary facilities\nin its navy yards, should go into the business of\nbuilding merchant ships, in competition with the\ncommercial ship builders. The United States Govern\nment owns an excellent airplane manufacturing plant\nin which it builds experimental planes for the navy.\nSuppose the Government should go into the airplane\nmanufacturing business for the general public? It\nwould be perfectly obvious to everybody that this\n\u25a0was something which the Government has no business\nto do.\nPrinting of Government documents, maps, postage\nstamps and money, are a proper function for the\nGovernment's printing establishmets. But when the\nGovernment of the United States engages in the busi\nness of printing return envelopes for private citizens,\nit is unfairly competing with the job printers of the\nnation. It would be unfair competition even if a fair\ncommercial rate were charged for the work; it is\nworse than unfair when this work is done for less\nthan cost.\nThe National Editorial Association, and practic\nally every other association of newspaper publishers\nand printers, have protested for years against this\npractice. This year a more determined effort than\never is being made to induce Congress just elected,\nif not the one already in office, to take Uncle Sam\nout of this petty competition with his nephews.\no\u2014o\u2014o\nSCRUBBING THE FACE OF EDUCATION\nTHE LITTLE RED SCHOOLHOUSE will have to\nstand a tremendous lot of remodeling before\nit can meet with the approval of the Federal\nOffice of Education. In fact, it probably won't even\nknow itself if it is made over in accordance with\ndirections furnished by Federal officials.\nThe old, rusty, dirty box stove, with a rusty stove\npipe, placed in the middle of the room, will have to\ngo. Instead, there will be a jacketed stove set in\nthe end wall. The two or three small window\u2019s on\neach side that characterized the old-fashioned school\ni must give way to an area of clear glass equal to one\nfifth of the floor space of the room. And all the\nwindows should be moved to the left side of the\nchildren as they sit at their desks.\nSeparate cloak rooms for boys and girls, with\nscreened lunch shelves are recommended whenever\npossible. So arc bookcases and first-aid cabinets.\nThe directions include floor plans and remodeling\nsome of them the product of school architects\nand State departments of education in Minnesota,\nArkansas and Alabama.\nWHAT BUILDS A STATE?\nAMONG the important factors that contribute to\nthe up-building of a state is the volume of pro\nduction. Among the older settled states of the\neast, stress is laid upon manufacturing and its\nallied industries. Out here in the northwest where\nstates are still new', production must play a necessary'\npart if the commonwealth is to make progress.\nEncouragement given to producers in the con\nsumption of their products is one way to help advance\nthe cause of any state. Down in Wyoming emphasis\nis being placed on sugar beet culture. In the press\ncomment appearing in the column following the\neditorial matter it is specifically slated that beet sugar\nbuilds Wyoming. The editorial utterance is taken\nfrom the Cheyenne Tribune-Leader and shows that the\nenterprising citizens of our sister state to the south arc\nappealing to the loyalty of the citizens of that state\nto use all Wyoming grown, produced and manufactured\nproducts where it is possible.\nThe argument is made that money spent for cane\nsugar does not come back to the state, but money\npaid for beet sugar produced by Wyoming remains and\nis used to advance its progress. It is a sound argu\nment and one that should appeal to all loyal citizens\nof Wyoming.\nIn like manner, Montana, also a state that pro\nduces many commodities, has the opportunity of keep\ning its money at home. By the use of home made and\ngrow n products, labor is employed, commercial enter\nprises are encouraged and industries are build up\nwhich reflect back upon the state.\nMontana also produces beet sugur. It produces\nmore than that commodity. There are the livestock\nproducers with their wool and lambs and cattle and\nfeeder stock. By eating more lamb the sheepman\nw'ill be encouraged to raise more and better stock.\nBy using the beet sugar the growers ami manufac\nturers are strengthened and become inclined to\nincrease their product. More men are employed. A\ngreater buying power is created and moro people will\ncome to live in Montana.\nBe loyal to the state in which you live. Where it\nis possible patronize home industry. Encourage t>y\npatronage the initiative that would build greater\nthings for the state.\nMontana raises vast quantities of beans. Let\nMontanans eat the beans raised in the state. Ask for\nthem.\nHere are two agricultural industries that will\nprofit much and the state will be benefited if the\npeople of the state ask for ana demand Montana raised\nproducts. It is a fine thing to express loyalty, but it\nis a practical thing at the same time to support home\nindustries.\u2014Miles City Star.\nA DOZEN YEARS LATER\nTOMORROW\u2019, just a dozen years to the day after\nEdward R. Kitts laid aside the business of kill\ning for his country's sake, that country will, in\na small measure, discharge its debt to the dashing\nyoung corporal who, on Sept. 26, 1918, on the blood\ndrenched and shell swept fields neur Epionville,\nFrance, dared and conquered a machine guii nest with\nits constant and terrible menace to the soldiers of the\nallies.\nAs fitting ceremonies in tin* Shrine temple Edward\nKitts will be decorated with what his country is\npleased to term the distinguished service cross. High\nofficials of state and city will be present and partici\npate, and if we know Ed Kitts, the least interested\nin the proceedings will be Kitts himself. He had\nlittle thought, when he worked himself across a path\nwhere death tsnd, that he would receive this high\nhonor from his country, and when he had done fcis\nshare, a mere duty as he saw it, and the deadly stream\nof lead from a machine gun had been silenced, ho\nconsidered it just another day.\nKitts is modest and the actual details of his\nexploit will not be known from his lips. Sufficient\nit is for us to accept the words upon the decoration\nns covering entirely the case. Those words are\n\"For V'alor.\"\nBut the decoration of itself docs not discharge\nthe nation's debt to Edward Kitts, lie is broken io\nhealth, suffering from wounds received in action\nand he is not a complaining person. He is carrying on,\ndoing his duty in civil life as he did it in military\nservice. Without detracting one whit from the honor\nand glory that is rightfully Edward Kitts\u2019 when he is\ndecorated tomorrow, let each one of us remember\nwith him his thousands of buddies who did their bit,\nand while the opportunity that came Kitts\u2019 way was\nnot thrown in the paths of all, they were equally\nentitled to the breaks. Kitts is entitled ns heroically\neurned to the honor that will be conferred upon him\ntomorrow and tho city anil his state aro proud of him\nas a citizen. We needed, back a dozen years or so\nago, men of the stamp of Kitts and We should ever\nlastingly thauk a kind Almighty that they were at\nhand.\nCorporal Kitts, we sulute you.\u2014Montana Record-\nHerald, Nov. 10, 1930.\no\u2014o\u2014o\nPOLITICS AND PERSONALITIES\nIN THE CONGRESS that convenes this December\nthere will be many varieties of that curious spec\nies known as the \"lame duck.\" A lame duck\nis a representative or senator who has met defeat in\nthe November elections but who, according to Con\nstitutional provisions, continues in office until the\nfollowing March 4. His position is not pleasant to\ncontemplate. He must look after the interests of\n\"the people who sent me here,\" just as though those\npeople had not already recalled him. His every speech,\nis a swan-song. His votes must be cast with an eye\nto the welfare of a constituency that has repudiated\nhim. He is, in short, an anomalous and obsolete\nfactor in representative government.\nIhe question arises: why isn't something done\nabout it? Something has been done, but not enough.\nSenator George Norris, of Nebraska, has successively\nintroduced five Senate resolutions providing for a\nconstitutional amendment that will, if adopted, cause\nthe newly elected Congress to convene in the\nJanuary following the November elections. It would\nalso advance Inauguration Day from March to Janu\nary. All five resolutions passed the Senate, the first\non February, 1923, and the last in June, 1929, and all\nw\u2019ent to the House for further action. But here is\nthe hitch. The House has never acted, despite the\nfact that some of its members ihave introduced\nsimilar resolutions.\nThe Norris Amendment now languishes in the\nHouse Committee on Election of President, Vice-\nPresident and Members of Congress. And the Ameri\ncan people, with the fortitude or apathy\u2014whichever\none chooses to call it \u2014that is bred of a long familiar\nity with the cumbersome processes of government\nstill suffer passively the evils of the lame duck\nsystem.\no\u2014o\u2014o-\nEditorial Pencil Pointers\nSome people look good in almost everything they\neat. J\nThey say Byrd came home broke. Must have been\na vacation instead of an expedition he was on.\nCarving the Thanksgiving turkey is like going on\na dry raid\u2014keep yourself dry and locate the joints.\nA few old settlers in Chicago can still remember\nwhen the big fire did not come from machine guns.\nOne way to stop over-production of wheat would\nbe to establish a Tad Polo golf course on each farm.\n\u201cI do not choose to pun,\u201d said Coolidge when\nasked to put a little moro humor into his paragraphs.\nBecause a man\u2019s clothos looTc like they had been\nslept in is no proof that he has just been to church.\nYears ago, when you wanted to poison people you\nput it into their coffee. Now you invito them down\ncellar.\nTHE -HARLEM NEWS, HARLEM, MONTANA\nU&cal-\nmmtm\nMrs. Jamco Ring of Havre was a\nSunday guest of relatives in Harlem.\nJ. O. Cronk of the Coburg region,\ntran-aeted business in Harlem, Wednes\nday.\nJoe \u2022'\u25a0\u2019chwaiier left Sunday for Minot,\nN. Dak., where he will spend the win\nter months.\nJack and Frank Olszewski of the\nHogeland farming country, were busi\nness callers in Harlem, Monday.\nMrs. M. D. Eastley, wife of the edi\ntor of The Hogeland Herald, was a\nHarlem business caller Saturday.\nMrs. J. M. Everett is enjoying a visit\nfrom her aister who arrived recently\nfrom the east to spend the winter here.\nMrs. Lucy Goodall, who has been ill\nat the local hospital for several weeks,\nhas gone to Missoula:, seeking surgical\nattention.\nBobby and Binkv Jessen, sons of Mr.\nand Mrs. Leonard Jessen of Havre,\nspent the week-end here visiting their\ngrandparents.\nMiss Claire Gleason, of the Zurich\nschool faculty, spent the week-end visit\ning at the J. M. Everett ranch home\nnear this city.\nMrs. Twete and her daughter, Mrs.\nSig Rasmussen returned Wednesday\nfrom a trip to the coast and are again\nat home on the Big Flat.\nMrs. Florence Holden spent several\ndays here last week visiting friends.\nShe left Saturday for Chinook where\nshe will reside this winter.\nMrs. Henry Plott of Malta spent sev\neral days here last week calling on old\nfriends and relatives. While here she\nwas the house guest of Mrs. W. J. j\nLawr.\nMr. and Mrs. W. .T. Jones and daugh\nter Helen, accompanied by the Misses!\nFlahaven and Dearey, drove to Great j\nFalls Friday evening, returning home\nSunday.\nMrs. F. M. Allen and son, Fred, were\nHarlem business callers from the Little j\nJewell district, Tuesday, coming in to\nbring turkeys for the Thanksgiving\nshipment.\nMrs. T. A. Marlow accompanied her;\ndaughter and son-in-law, Mr. and Mrs.\nEdmond Smith of Coburg, on a week\nend trip to Great Falls, leaving here\nSaturday morning.\nRaymond Holden, prominent stock\nfarmer of the north country, had the\nmisfortune to break his ankle when he\njumped from the Equity platform at\nHogeland, Saturday afternoon.\n'The J. W. Epler family have decided\nto not remain in Chinook where they\nrecently moved from Harlem, but arc\nleaving for the western part of the j\nstate seeking a business location.\nConstruction work on the Agency\nhospital ceased for the winter last Fri-\nday and the transients who had been 1\nemployed on the job have left for their\nvarious homes or for new employment.\nArmistice Day was observed at Har\nlem schools Tuesday afternoon by spec\nial exercises at the Lincoln School, the\npupils participating, and by an Armis\ntice Day address by Supt. Seibel at the\nhigh school.\nA. O. Running, E. P. Ekegren and\nClarence Watkins returned Tuesday\nafternoon from the Rockies where they\nspent a week on a deer hunting trip.\nEach hunter brought home a fine\nblack-tail deer.\nMr. and Mrs. Alec Schwalicr left\nSaturday for Los Angeles where they\nwill spend the winter. Mr. Schwalier,\nwho has been in poor health for some\nmonths, hopes to recover his strength\nin the milder climate.\nBishop H. H. H. Fox of Billings will\nbe in Harlem, Tuesday, Nov. 18, and i\nhold Episcopalian services that eve\nning at the Presbyterian church. The\nservices w\u2019ill be public and everyone is\ncordially invited to attend.\nWalter Lawr, son of Mr. and Mrs.\nW. J. Lawr, who is attending Airtech\nSchool at San Diego, writes that he\nmade his first solo flight last week\nafter ten hours of flying. Walter was\ngraduated from Harlem High last\nspring and is taking an air pilot's,\ncourse at the California school.\nIndian summer weather gave way to\na touch of winter Tuesday when snow\nbegan falling late in the afternoon.\nThe temperature remains fairly high,\nbut. considerable moisture has fallen in\nthe form of rain and snow since that\ntime. Stockmen have been warned that\nthe condition is liable to last for several\ndays.\nMiss Belinda Blackseth has been ap-\npointed to fill the vacancy in the facul\nty of the Turner high school, created by\nthe resignation of Miss Bentley, who\nhas returned to her home in Minnesota.\nM iss Blackseth is a relative of Mr. and\nMrs. A. O. Ronning of Harlem and has\noften visited here. She was graduated\nfrom the University of Minnesota last\nspring.\nG. O. Brandvold left Tuesday after\nnoon for Rochester and other Minne\nsota points to visit relatives, from\nwhere he and Mrs. Brandvold will de\npart for Arizona where they plan to\nspend the winter months. Mr. Brand\nvoid returned to Harlem a week ago\nto attend to business matters and get\nan extension to his leave of absence as\ncashier of the local bank, but plans to\nreturn here, if his health permits, in\nthe early spring.\nDr. Smith, dentist of Harlem, operat\ning a chain of dental offices thraont\nthe state, gives you dental work \u00abt\nprices that arc a substantial saving.\nCall for free examination. \u2014Adv.\nGRAND THEATRE\nHARLEM\nW\nMaude W\nHenderson Players j I\n2 NIGHTS I\nSTARTS B\n11 Thursday, Nov. 20 j I\nIN TWO GREAT PEATS H\nOPENING IN II\n5 Perfect Stranger i H\na FUEL OP LAUGHS\n1a j H. S.\u2014 soc CHILDREN 25c jjyg\nB A \u2018-cr.--- -r. t-.T\u2019\nBen Savage arrived in Harlem this\nweek for a visit with his mother and\nsister.\nThe initial meeting of the Girl\nScouts was called Wednesday after\nschool when the Misses Kreider, Dcar\ncy and McKcnty met with all girls who\nwere desirous of taking up scout work.\nTwenty-five girls reported and were\nvery enthusiastic over the work out\nlined. 'The American Legion Auxiliary\nis sponsoring the troop.\nOrpheum Theatre, Chinook\n7 P. M. AND 9 P. M.\nPROGRAM FOR WEEK STARTING NOV. 16\nSUNDAY AND MONDAY, NOV. 16 AND 17\nRamon Navarro in\n\u201cDEVIL MAY CARE\u201d\nTUESDAY AND WEDNESDAY, NOV. 18 AND 19\n\u201cCOMMON CLAY\u201d\nFOX SPECIAL\nTHURSDAY AND FRIDAY, NOV. 20 AND 21\n\u201cThe Kibitzers 9\nAn \u201cA\u201d Class Comedy\nSATURDAY, NOVEMBER 22\nReginald Denny in\n\u201cEmbarrassing Moments\u2019\nBENNY RUBIN COMEDY\nMATlNEE\u2014Saturday and Sunday\u20143 P. M.\n15c and 35e\nRUTTREY\u2019S\n\u2018THE QUALITY STORE\u201d\nFRIDAY and SATURDAY\nCorn Flakes eq r\n10 PACKAGES\nPancake Flour 3^r.\nROBB ROSS\u20144 lb PKG *-J*JK*\nSyrup 69c\nKARO OR AMAIZO\u2014I GAL w v w\nCandy 25c\n5c BARS\u2014ANY KIND\u20146 FOR\nOnions Qft r\n40 POUNDS W\nECONOMISTS FOR THE PEOPLE\n\u2019Friday, November 14, 1930\nMiss Dora Schilling spent the week\nend at the C. M. Dolvcn home.\n8. O. Bengston of East End, Canada,\ndrove here Wednesday on business and\nto visit his uncles C. M. Dolven and\nA. M. Dolven.\nA group of Harlem Eastern Btars\ndrove to Chinook, Wednesday evening\nin response to an invitation from the\nchapter there to attend a meeting and\ncard party.","height":"23712","width":"16952"}}
